==English==
===Etymology===
Anglo-Saxon ''[[crypel]]'', cognate with ''[[cr&#275;opan]]'', "to creep", "to crawl"; confer Dutch ''[[kreupel]]'', German ''[[Krüppel]]'', Old Norse ''[[cryppill]]''.

===Pronunciation===
*Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-ɪpəl|-ɪpəl]]

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# a [[person]] who is [[severe]]ly [[impair]]ed in his [[physical]] [[ability|abilities]] because of [[deformation]], [[injury]], or [[amputation]] of parts of the body.
#:''He returned from war a '''cripple'''.''
#  a shortened [[wood]]en [[stud]] or [[brace]] used to construct the portion of a wall above a [[door]] or above and below a [[window]].

====Translations====
{{rfc-trans}}
*Finnish: [[invalidi]], [[vammainen]]
*German: [[Krüppel]] ''m'' (1)

===Verb===
{{en-verb|crippl|ing}}

# to make someone a cripple; to cause someone to become a cripple
#:''The car bomb '''crippled''' five passers-by.''
# (''figurative'') to [[damage]] [[serious]]ly; to [[destroy]]
#:''My ambitions were '''crippled''' by a lack of money.''
# to release a [[product]] (especially a [[computer program]]) with reduced functionality, in some cases, making the item essentially worthless.
#:''The word processor was released in a '''crippled''' demonstration version that did not allow you to save.''

====Translations====
{{rfc-trans}}
*Finnish: [[vammauttaa]] (1), [[tuhota]] (2)
*German: [[verkrüppeln]] (1), [[zunichte]] machen (2)

